'''Ariadna Thalia Sodi Miranda''' ({{IPA-es|a<U+027E>i<U+02C8>a<U+00F0>na ta<U+02C8>li.a <U+02C8>so<U+00F0>i mi<U+02C8><U+027E>anda}}; born August 26, 1971), known [[mononymous person|mononymously]] as '''Thal<U+00ED>a''', is a [[Mexico|Mexican]] singer, songwriter, published author, actress and entrepreneur, who has sung in various languages including Spanish, English, Portuguese, French and Filipino.<ref name="Billboard 1997">{{cite news|url=http://books.google.com.gt/books?id=oxMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA30&dq=Thal%C3%ADa+to+release+Arrasando&hl=es&sa=X&ei=O8qaT4yuGOK02gXws9mNDw&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Thal%C3%ADa%20to%20release%20Arrasando&f=false|title=THE BILLBOARD STAR AWARD : Thal<U+00ED>a <nowiki>|</nowiki> The Mexican Singer/Actress Has Risen From Kiddie Pop To Soap Operas To International Status|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Google Books]]|date=March 2011|accessdate=August 11, 2012|language=}}</ref>

She is recognized as the most successful female solo Mexican singer by Latin [[media conglomerate]]s such as [[Univision Communications|Univision]], [[Televisa]], and [[Azteca (multimedia company)|Azteca]],<ref name="Oye">{{cite news|url=http://www.oyemexico.com/nota/25-mexicanos-mas-influyentes-en-la-musica/|title=25 mexicanos m<U+00E1>s influyentes en la m<U+00FA>sica|work=Oyemexico.com|date=|accessdate=August 10, 2012|language=spanish}}</ref><ref name="Televisa">{{cite news|url=http://especiales.televisa.com/musica/noticias/512948/thalia-con-nuevo-disco/|title=Thal<U+00ED>a con nuevo disco
|work=[[Televisa]]|date=|accessdate=August 27, 2012|language=spanish}}</ref><ref name="TV Azteca">{{cite news|url=http://www.azteca.com/notas/vengalaalegria/128322/thalia-una-de-las-mexicanas-mas-tocadas|title=Ellas son las mexicanas m<U+00E1>s tocadas|work=[[Azteca (multimedia company)|Azteca]]|author=Ana Karen Grande Benavides|date=August 30, 2012|accessdate=August 10, 2012|language=spanish}}</ref> while she is often referred to as the "Queen of Latin Pop" by the media internationally, mainly because of her legacy within the [[Latin pop]] music scene of the last 25 years.<ref name="abullseyeview">{{cite news| url=http://abullseyeview.com/playlist-target-interview-thalia-queen-latin-pop/ }}</ref><ref name="Queen of latin pop">{{cite news|url=http://anodis.com/galeria.asp?id=7|title=Thal<U+00ED>a, reina del pop latino|work=Anodis.com|date=|accessdate=August 11, 2012|language=spanish}}</ref> As a solo artist, she has sold over 40 million records worldwide, being considered one of the best-selling Latin musicians of all time.<ref name="40 million HTV">{{cite news|url=http://www.htv.com/noticias/thalia-cantara-en-portugues|title=Thal<U+00ED>a cantar<U+00E1> en portugu<U+00E9>s|work=[[HispanicTV]] (HTV)|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System Latin America]]|date=December 12, 2012|accessdate=December 20, 2012|language=}}</ref><ref name="NBC">{{cite news|url=http://m.nbc.com/news/20_97690.shtml#ckchk=1|title=NBC ENTERTAINMENT NEWS|work=[[NBC]]|year=2011|accessdate=December 18, 2012|language=}}</ref><ref name="Huffington Post">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/02/singer-thalia-gets-persona_n_1071683.html|title=Singer Thalia Gets Personal, Emotional In 'Growing Stronger'|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=November 2, 2011|accessdate=August 10, 2012|language=|first=Nicki|last=Gostin}}</ref><ref>http://entertainment/music/article/Thalia-enjoys-a-career-evolution-4389871.php</ref> She has had 28 Top 10 singles, 15 of which went to No.1 and she has received numerous accolades including five [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|Latin Billboard]] awards, several [[Premios Juventud]] awards and various [[Latin Grammy]] nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywood.patch.com/groups/arts-and-entertainment/p/thalia-queen-of-latin-pop-to-receive-hollywood-walk-of-fame-star |title=Patch |publisher=Hollywood.patch.com |date= |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref>

Apart from her success as a recording artist, Thal<U+00ED>a has also had a successful career in acting, as she starred in a variety of soap operas (known as [[telenovelas]]) that have aired in over 180 countries.<ref name="Especial de Televisa">{{cite news|url=http://especiales.televisa.com/fotos/thalia/37581/|title=Thalia|work=[[Televisa]]|date=|accessdate=August 10, 2012|language=spanish}}</ref><ref name="Houston">{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/spanish/entertainment/article/Thal-a-busca-la-liberaci-n-1726321.php|title=Thalia busca la liberaci<U+00F3>n|first=Dorantes|last=David|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=September 27, 2009|accessdate=August 10, 2012|language=spanish}}</ref> During the decade of the 1990s, she was converted into a television icon and was publicly referred to as the "Queen of [[telenovelas]]" by the [[mass media]] around the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/27/world/mere-soap-opera-it-s-mexican-magic-in-tagalog.html | work=The New York Times | first=Edward A. | last=Gargan | title=Mere Soap Opera? It's Mexican Magic (in Tagalog) | date=August 27, 1996}}</ref> She was also reported to be the most successful and best-paid [[telenovela]] actress, as stated by [[Televisa]], the largest mass media company in the Spanish-speaking world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laprensa.com.bo/diario/entretendencias/escena/20111018/thalia-reina-de-las-novelas_9504_15909.html |title=Thalia, reina de las novelas |publisher=Laprensa.com.bo |date=October 18, 2011 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e-jJZGzobpI&feature=relmfu |title=Thalia - La Historia Detras Del Mito Pt. 3 of 5 |publisher=YouTube |date=September 13, 2011 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref>

In 2008, the British tabloid [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|''The Sun'']] named her one of "the 50 female singers who will never be forgotten"<ref name="The Sun">{{cite news|url=http://www.letras.com.br/noticia/as-50-cantoras-que-nunca-serao-esquecidas_334|title=As 50 cantoras que nunca ser<U+00E3>o esquecidas|work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|date=May 13, 2008|accessdate=August 10, 2012|language=portuguese}}</ref> and in 2011, [[Terra Networks]] included her in their list of "the most powerful and iconic women in music".<ref name="Terra Networks Influential">{{cite news|url=http://musica.terra.com/las-mujeres-mas-fuertes-e-iconicas-de-la-musica,aa86dad93eee5310VgnVCM20000099f154d0RCRD.html|title=Las mujeres m<U+00E1>s fuertes e ic<U+00F3>nicas de la m<U+00FA>sica|work=[[Terra Networks]]|date=March 8, 2012|accessdate=August 11, 2012|page=2|language=spanish}}</ref> She is also an occasional fashion designer and has her own nationally syndicated radio show, while she is an accomplished author having released four books, one of them being her personal memoir. 
On December 5, 2013 she was honored with a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], as a recognition for her successful career in music and entertainment.<ref name="Huffington Post Walk">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/26/thalia-hollywood-walk-of-fame_n_1628329.html|title=Thal<U+00ED>a To Get Star On Hollywood Walk Of Fame|last=Lopez|first=Michael|work=Huffington Post|date=June 26, 2012|accessdate=August 10, 2012|language=}}</ref><ref name="Walk of fame Tribue Pakistan">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/398205/honourees-announced-for-hollywood-walk-of-fame-2013/|title=Honourees announced for Hollywood Walk of Fame 2013|work=[[The Express Tribune]]|date=June 23, 2012|accessdate=September 10, 2012|language=}}</ref>

==Early life==
[[File:Santa feconj Mexico City.jpg|thumb|Thalia's birth city, [[Mexico City]].]]
Thal<U+00ED>a was born on August 26, 1971 in [[Mexico City, Mexico]]. She is the youngest of five daughters of Yolanda Miranda Mange, a painter who was Thalia's manager from 1980 to 1999; and Ernesto Sodi Pallares, a scientist, doctor of pathology, criminologist, and writer. Her four sisters are [[Laura Zapata]] (daughter of Guillermo Zapata P<U+00E9>rez de Utrera), Federica, Gabriela, and Ernestina Sodi.

When she turned one year old, Thal<U+00ED>a appeared in her first TV commercial in Mexico. When she turned four, she began taking ballet and piano classes at the [[National Conservatory of Music of Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Por Notimex |url=http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/articulo/celebrara-thalia-su-cumpleanos-40 |title=Celebrar<U+00E1> Thal<U+00ED>a su cumplea<U+00F1>os 40 [Thal<U+00ED>a&#93; - 25/08/2011 &#124; Peri<U+00F3>dico Z<U+00F3>calo |publisher=Zocalo.com.mx |date=August 25, 2011 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> Thal<U+00ED>a's father suffered from [[diabetes]] when Thal<U+00ED>a was only six years old and died in 1977. Years later, Thalia realized that her father's death traumatized her drastically, since she couldn't talk to anyone for a whole year. This led to her being diagnosed with CDH, [[childhood disintegrative disorder]], which belongs to a series of developmental disorders caused by [[autism spectrum]].<ref>http://www.casatelenovela.com/2008/04/la_cantante_y_actriz_thalia_fu.html</ref> Her mother took her to many psychologists at an early age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.generaccion.com/noticia/127628/thalia-enmudecio-tras-muerte-su-padre |title=Thalia enmudeci<U+00F3> tras la muerte de su padre |publisher=Generaccion.com |date= |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvynovelas.com/noticias/356657/thalia-confiesa-estuvo-muda-ano|work=TVyNovelas.com |title=Revista TVyNovelas |publisher=Tvynovelas.com |date= |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref>

Thal<U+00ED>a went to [[Liceo Franco Mexicano]] elementary school, where she learned to speak French and Spanish fluently at a very young age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://musica.univision.com/artistas/thalia/biografia |title=Biograf<U+00ED>a de Thal<U+00ED>a &#124; Univision M<U+00FA>sica |publisher=Musica.univision.com |date= |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> In 1976, a year before her father's death, she appeared in a Mexican movie ''La guerra de los pasteles'' ("War of Cakes"), although her name doesn't appear in the film credits.<ref>http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0180724/fullcredits#cast</ref> As Thal<U+00ED>a was also practicing various sports during her childhood, she was inspired by Romanian record-setting athlete [[Nadia Comaneci]]. Nadia's record gave Thal<U+00ED>a the desire to follow a career in entertainment. Her eldest sister, Laura Zapata, was also a singer and she used to take Thal<U+00ED>a with her to the theatre when she was a child; she passionately embraced acting at a very young age.

==Life and career==

===1981<U+2013>1989: Career beginnings and the Timbiriche era===

In 1981, when Thal<U+00ED>a was nine years old, she was incorporated as a vocalist in a children's group named Pac Man, which was formed in order to participate in a popular music festival,  known as ''Juguemos a cantar'' ("Let's play at singing"), a TV program by [[Televisa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mx.hola.com/biografias/thalia/biografia/ |title=Thal<U+00ED>a. Noticias, fotos y biograf<U+00ED>a de Thal<U+00ED>a |publisher=Mx.hola.com |date= |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> Later, Pac Man changed their band name to "Din-Din". Thal<U+00ED>a performed various times along with Din-Din in occasional events and parties, touring all over Mexico. The band recorded a total of 4 studio albums between 1982 and 1983 (''En acci<U+00F3>n'', ''Recordando el Rock and Roll'', ''Somos alguien muy especial'' and ''Pitubailando''), and later it was disbanded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=334256 |title=Thalia Din-Din En Accion Mexico vinyl LP album (LP record) (334256) |publisher=Eil.com |date=March 14, 2002 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=387057 |title=Thalia Pitubailando Mexico 12" vinyl single (12 inch record / Maxi-single) (387057) |publisher=Eil.com |date=March 14, 2002 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=387069 |title=Thalia Somos Alguien Muy Especial Mexico vinyl LP album (LP record) (387069) |publisher=Eil.com |date=March 14, 2002 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=387050 |title=Thalia Recordando El Rock And Roll Mexico 12" vinyl single (12 inch record / Maxi-single) (387050) |publisher=Eil.com |date=March 14, 2002 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref>

After Din-Din broke up in 1984, Thal<U+00ED>a participated as a solo artist in two annual music festivals of ''Juguemos a cantar''. In 1984, she placed second there with her interpretation of <U+00AB>Moderna ni<U+00F1>a del rock<U+00BB> ("Modern rock girl"); this brought her the opportunity to participate in the chorus of the popular musical ''Vaselina'', a child version of the successful musical ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]'', in which the band [[Timbiriche]] was acting and singing. The line-up of the band consisted of Sasha S<U+00F6>kol, Benny Ibarra, Erik Rub<U+00ED>n, Diego Schoening, Mariana Garza and [[Paulina Rubio]]. [[Timbiriche]] was highly promoted at the time by [[Televisa]], one of the most massive media enterprises globally and the most important in the Spanish-speaking world. Some time later, Thal<U+00ED>a obtained the protagonist role of Sandy Dee in the musical, and she performed in 500 theater presentations of ''Vaselina'' along with [[Timbiriche]].

In 1986, after the departure of Sasha S<U+00F6>kol from Timbiriche, Thal<U+00ED>a became a member of the band. By that time, Timbiriche had already recorded five albums. In the following year, Thal<U+00ED>a was offered to participate in the [[telenovela]] ''Pobre se<U+00F1>orita Limantour''; this production was actually Thal<U+00ED>a's debut as a TV actress. However, she appeared in only one episode.<ref>http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0211843/fullcredits#cast</ref> In the same year, she recorded with [[Timbiriche]] the principal theme of the [[Young-adult fiction|juvenile]] [[telenovela]] ''[[Quincea<U+00F1>era (telenovela)|Quincea<U+00F1>era]]'' ("Fifteen-year-old"), in which Thal<U+00ED>a was the co-protagonist with the role of Beatriz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alma-latina.net/Quinceanera/Quinceanera.shtml |title=Quincea<U+0144>era - telenovela |publisher=Alma-latina.net |date= |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> The TV series was awarded as the <U+00AB>Best telenovela<U+00BB> by "Premios TVyNovelas" in 1988 and Thal<U+00ED>a was awarded as "the best new actress of 1988".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uWQELqT9kGo |title=THALIA recibe premio tvnovelas por actriz revelacion en quincea<U+00F1>era |publisher=YouTube |date=February 13, 2010 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref>

With [[Timbiriche]], Thal<U+00ED>a recorded four studio albums: ''Timbiriche VII'' (1987), the double album ''Timbiriche VIII y IX'' (1988) and ''Los cl<U+00E1>sicos de Timbiriche'' (1989). The last one is a compilation of the band's greatest hits, recorded originally in 1987, with new symphonic arrangements as it included the participation of Mexico's philharmonic orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.esmas.com/ritmoson-latino/artistas/251843?page=1 |title=Ritmoson |publisher=.esmas.com |date= |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> In 1989, Thal<U+00ED>a departed from Timbiriche.<ref>{{cite web|author=Eunice Mart<U+00ED>nez Arias |url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/284817.vuelven-a-vivir-el-exito.html |title=Vuelven a vivir el <U+00E9>xito |publisher=Elsiglodetorreon.com.mx |date=July 6, 2007 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref> In that year, she also starred in another TV series, ''Luz y sombra'' ("Light and shadow"), which was her first protagonist role.<ref>http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0211824/</ref> Some time later she visited Los Angeles in order to take English courses in the University of California. She also attended music, singing, acting and dancing classes before beginning her career as a solo artist.

===1990<U+2013>1993: First albums as a solo artist===

In 1990, Thal<U+00ED>a returned to Mexico and released her first studio album as a [[solo artist]], self-titled  ''[[Thal<U+00ED>a (1990 album)|Thal<U+00ED>a]]'', which was produced by Alfredo D<U+00ED>az Ordaz, and published by [[Fonovisa Records|Fonovisa]], [[Televisa]]'s record label. From that album, she released a total of four singles that became huge radio hits : "Amarillo Azul", "Pienso en Ti", "Un Pacto Entre Los Dos" and "Saliva". The two last tracks were co-written by her and D<U+00ED>az Ordaz and they were considered as provocative at the time ("Un Pacto Entre Los Dos" was even labeled as a song with occult Satan-worship lyrics by various [[Far-right politics|far-right parties]]).<ref>http://www.revista-contacto.info/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9622:thalia-precursora-de-lady-gaga&catid=117:ultimas-noticias&Itemid=596</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://musica.univision.com/fotos/curiosas/slideshow/2011-08-25/thalia-40-anos-canciones-trayectoria-fotos-cumpleanos |title=Thal<U+00ED>a. 40 a<U+00F1>os, 40 canciones - Univision M<U+00FA>sica |publisher=Musica.univision.com |date= |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref>

In September 1991, Thal<U+00ED>a released her second studio album, ''[[Mundo de cristal]]'', which marks Thal<U+00ED>a's last project in collaboration with Alfredo D<U+00ED>az Ordaz. Four songs became radio singles from the album, and all of them had big radio impact in Mexico. Due to the success of the singles, the album was certified as double gold in Thal<U+00ED>a's native country, Mexico. In the same year, Thal<U+00ED>a was co-presenter of the late Spanish show ''VIP Noche'', along with Spanish presenter Emilio Arag<U+00F3>n, produced by [[Telecinco]].<ref>http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0321004/fullcredits#cast</ref>

In October 1992, she released her third studio album and her last under the same label, entitled ''[[Love (Thal<U+00ED>a album)|Love]]'', which was recorded in Spain and it was produced by Luis Carlos Esteban. The album spread six singles, that had huge radio impact: "Sangre", "Love", "No Trates de Enga<U+00F1>arme", "Flor de Juventud", "Mar<U+00ED>a Mercedes" (official theme of the TV series), and "La Vida en Rosa" ([[La vie en rose]]), the last one being a Spanish-French cover of the classic French song originally performed by [[Edith Piaf]]. Thal<U+00ED>a wrote the song "Sangre" inspired in D<U+00ED>az Ordaz, with whom she had broken up her sentimental relation. The album was praised by the critics, as it was an artistic evolution for Thal<U+00ED>a, who experimented for the first time in different [[music genres]], especially [[electronic music]]. The album reached number 15 on [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard's]] ''[[Latin Pop Albums]]'' in 1993.<ref>http://www.allrovi.com/music/album/love-mw0000172049|work=allrovi.com</ref> In Mexico, it sold over 200,000 copies in the first month upon its release and very soon it reached the platinum and gold certification.

===1994<U+2013>1999: International breakout ===
In 1994, during the successful transmission of ''[[Marimar (telenovela)|Marimar]]'', Thal<U+00ED>a signed a contract with the record label [[EMI]] in order to prepare her fourth studio album that was entitled ''[[En <U+00E9>xtasis]]''. The album was released in October 1995. ''En <U+00E9>xtasis'' was produced with the aid of celebrated producers such as [[Emilio Estefan, Jr.]] (husband of the famous Cuban singer [[Gloria Estefan]]) and <U+00D3>scar L<U+00F3>pez.<ref>http://books.google.com.mx/books?id=STjcB_f7CVcC&lpg=PA835&dq=thalia%20m%C3%A9xico&hl=es&pg=PA835#v=onepage&q=thalia&f=false</ref> The album spawned a total of seven singles including "[[Piel morena]]", "[[Am<U+00E1>ndote]]", "[[Maria la del Barrio (song)|Mar<U+00ED>a la del barrio]]", "[[Quiero hacerte el amor]]", "[[Gracias a Dios (song)|Gracias a Dios]], "[[Me Faltas T<U+00FA>]]" and "[[L<U+00E1>grimas (song)|L<U+00E1>grimas]]". 
 
[[Piel morena]] became a huge international hit<ref>http://www.allmusic.com/artist/p29449/charts-awards/billboard-singles</ref> apart from being voted as the best Spanish song ever in the United States from a poll relaized by mass media company [[Univision]]. It must also be added that Thal<U+00ED>a was more oriented to the [[latin pop]] music genre in that album, even though it was influenced by various music genres.

The broadcast of the [[telenovelas]] "[[Mar<U+00ED>a Mercedes (telenovela)|Mar<U+00ED>a Mercedes]]", "[[Marimar (telenovela)|Marimar]]" and "[[Mar<U+00ED>a la del barrio]]" had already converted Thal<U+00ED>a to a global television phenomenon by the end of 1996. In January 1997, she released her first compilation album entitled ''[[Nandito Ako]]'', which contains four songs recorded in [[Tagalog]], a major language of the [[Philippines]], five English versions from various tracks from the album [[En <U+00E9>xtasis]] and a Spanish remix of the song [[Am<U+00E1>ndote]]. The only single that was released from this album was ''Nandito Ako''. The album became a commercial success in the Philippines as a result of Thal<U+00ED>a's growing popularity, reaching platinum status set by the [[Philippine Association of the Record Industry]].

In July 1997, Thal<U+00ED>a's fifth studio album was released, under the title ''[[Amor a la mexicana]]'', produced again by [[Emilio Estefan]], and including songs that became classic over the years like <U+00AB>[[Mujer Latina]]<U+00BB>, <U+00AB>[[De d<U+00F3>nde soy]]<U+00BB>, <U+00AB>[[Por amor (Thal<U+00ED>a song)|Por amor]]<U+00BB>, <U+00AB>[[Noches sin luna]]<U+00BB> and <U+00AB>[[Amor a la Mexicana (song)|Amor a la mexicana]]<U+00BB>. The album became a pure commercial success,<ref>http://www.allmusic.com/album/amor-a-la-mexicana-r278142/charts-awards</ref> while the first single of the album ("[[Amor a la Mexicana (song)|Amor a la mexicana]]") became a number one hit in 14 countries. With Amor a la mexicana, Thal<U+00ED>a was able to bring her music and establish her projects in difficult markets like those of France, [[Belgium]], [[Switzerland]], [[Greece]], [[Hungary]], [[Turkey]], [[Poland]], [[Portugal]], Italy and all the Spanish-speaking countries.<ref>http://anodis.com/galeria.asp?id=7</ref>

After the success of ''Amor a la mexicana'', Thal<U+00ED>a recorded the Spanish and Portuguese versions of the song <U+00AB>Journey to the Past<U+00BB>, produced by [[Atlantic Records]], as a part of the soundtrack of the [[Fox Animation Studios]] movie [[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'' (1997).

In the following year, Thal<U+00ED>a starred for the first time in a movie in English, named "Mambo Caf<U+00E9>", written and directed by Reuben Gonz<U+00E1>lez.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1998_Nov_16/ai_53220016/ }}</ref><ref>http://www.thefreelibrary.com/%27Mambo+Cafe%27+Wraps+Principle+Photography%3B+Kushner-Locke+to+Distribute...-a053625991</ref> ''Mambo Caf<U+00E9>'' premiered in January 2000 in Mexico, Greece and Russia, distributed by Kushner Locke Entertainment.<ref>http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=7847&tabla=espectaculos</ref>

In 1999, after ''Mambo Caf<U+00E9>'', Thal<U+00ED>a returned in television with [[telenovela]] ''[[Rosalinda (telenovela)|Rosalinda]]''. "Rosalinda" was considered to be [[Televisa]]'s most expensive production ever by that time, as well as the most exported in foreign countries, as it was sold in over 180 countries. In an interview of that period Thal<U+00ED>a commented: <U+00AB>The telenovelas are the ones that opened the doors of the world for me, because the audience of telenovelas is much more passionate than the audience of cinema. What's more, television is free<U+00BB>.<ref>http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/15327/Thalia+llena+su+mundo.htm</ref>

===2000<U+2013>2005: Marriage, crossover and first tour in the United States===
Emilio Estefan also produced Thal<U+00ED>a's sixth studio album, ''[[Arrasando]]'', released on April 25, 2000, which was very successful. It spawned the singles "[[Entre el mar y una estrella]]", "[[Regresa a m<U+00ED>]]", "[[Arrasando (song)|Arrasando]]" and "[[Reencarnaci<U+00F3>n]]". Thal<U+00ED>a was nominated in the [[Latin Grammy]] category as the "Best Female Pop Artist of the Year". The album received one Latin Grammy nomination and it won in its category as the "Best Sound Engineered Album of the year". The singles of this album were huge hits. In 2001 she was nominated for her record ''Arrasando'' and won a Lo Nuestro award in the category of People's Prize, and was the first artist to whom an innovative award from Billboard Awards for Latin Music was given, the "Star Award".

On May 4, 2001, the President of the United States, [[George W. Bush]], invited her to a party celebrating [[Cinco de mayo]] organized at the [[White House]], where she interpreted a medley of popular Mexican songs with a Mexican mariachi band.

On August 28, 2001, expressing her love for her country of birth, Mexico, she released her album ''[[Thal<U+00ED>a con banda: Grandes <U+00E9>xitos|Con Banda: Grandes <U+00C9>xitos]]'': a "greatest hits" album, but recorded with the typical Mexican "banda" sound. "Amor a la Mexicana" banda version was released as a single. The album was nominated for a Latin Grammy for "Best Banda Album" at the 3rd Annual Latin Grammy Awards in 2002.

Her seventh studio album, self-titled ''[[Thal<U+00ED>a (2002 album)|Thal<U+00ED>a]]'', was released on May 21, 2002. It was largely written and produced by [[Est<U+00E9>fano]]. Buoyed by a pair of chart-topping singles ("[[T<U+00FA> y Yo (song)|T<U+00FA> y Yo]]" and "[[No me ense<U+00F1>aste]]") and a top-ten hit ("[[<U+00BF>A qui<U+00E9>n le importa?]]") (cover of [[Alaska y Dinarama]]), this album hit number one for 6 consecutive weeks on the [[Top Latin Albums]] chart, reaching number eleven on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart and 2x Multi-Platinum status with sales in the U.S. of 200,000 copies. It was nominated in one [[Latin Grammy]] category <U+2013> "[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album, Female|Female Pop Vocal Album]]", and in four [[2003 Latin Billboard Music Awards|Latin Billboard]] categories <U+2013> "Pop Track Female" and "Tropical Track Female" for "No Me Ense<U+00F1>aste", [[2003 Latin Billboard Music Awards#Your World Award (Premio Tu Mundo)|"Your World Award"]], and [[2003 Latin Billboard Music Awards#Female|"Female Pop Album"]], for ''Thal<U+00ED>a'', winning the last two awards. "No Me Ense<U+00F1>aste" reached at No. 1 in Billboard's [[Hot Latin Tracks]] chart.

On February 25, 2003, she released her first remix album, ''[[Thal<U+00ED>a's Hits Remixed]]''. This album contains some [[remix]]es of her ''EMI era'' hits, such as "Amor a la Mexicana", "Piel Morena", "No Me Ense<U+00F1>aste" and "T<U+00FA> y Yo." It also contains the English version of "Arrasando", called "It's My Party". Furthermore, it includes the previously unreleased medley that Thal<U+00ED>a had recorded especially for her 2001 Latin Grammy Awards performance, but was later cancelled, due to the [[September 11 attacks]].

[[File:Thal<U+00ED>a in concert2.jpg|thumb|upright|Thal<U+00ED>a in the ''High Voltage Tour'' Los Angeles concert on May 14, 2004]]
On July 8, 2003, Thal<U+00ED>a released her eighth studio album and the first one in English, the self-titled ''[[Thal<U+00ED>a (English album)|Thal<U+00ED>a]]'', featuring the rapper [[Fat Joe]] in "[[I Want You (Thal<U+00ED>a song)|I Want You/Me Pones Sexy]]". "[[Baby, I'm in Love/Alguien Real]]", "[[Don't Look Back (Thal<U+00ED>a song)|Don't Look Back]]" and "[[Cerca de ti (song)|Cerca De Ti]]" were singles too. The album landed at No. 11 in The Billboard 200.  The song "[[I Want You (Thal<U+00ED>a song)|I Want You]]" entered the [[American Top 40]] with Ryan Seacrest and even reached the top 10 during that year. The song also entered the American [[Billboard Top 100]] Singles Charts that year.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Thal<U+00ED>a Hits Billboard|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=thal<U+00ED>a|chart=all}} |work=Billboard}}</ref> She won an [[Winter Music Conference|International Dance Music Award]] for her club-hit "[[Dance Dance (The Mexican)]]".

On February 10, 2004, Thal<U+00ED>a released her first official ''[[Greatest Hits (Thal<U+00ED>a album)|Greatest Hits]]'' album, and "[[Cerca de ti (song)|Cerca de ti]]" and "[[Acci<U+00F3>n y Reacci<U+00F3>n]]" were the singles from this album. In April and May, she toured USA and Mexico with her "[[High Voltage Tour]]".

Her ninth studio album, ''[[El Sexto Sentido]]'', was released on July 19, 2005 and recorded mostly in Spanish, but with a few of the songs sung in English as well. It was reported to be the most expensive music album produced in Latin America in 2005. It had mild success, although the sound and the overall result make it one of her most integrated projects. "[[Amar sin ser amada]]" was the first single of the album and is considered as an infectious rock-edged [[tango music|tango]]-based song. "[[Un alma sentenciada]]", the second single of the album, is a feverish and, at points, hyperdramatic ballad. The explosive "[[Seducci<U+00F3>n]]" ("Seduction") and "Olvidame" were also releases as singles, gaining considerable success. The album was also certified gold in Argentina, Greece and Mexico and double platinum in the United States.

===2006<U+2013>2008: ''The Conexi<U+00F3>n Thal<U+00ED>a Radio Show'', Lyme disease and ''Lunada''===
In 2006, the album received a reloaded version, ''[[El Sexto Sentido#El Sexto Sentido: Re+Loaded|El Sexto Sentido: Re+Loaded]]''. Thal<U+00ED>a was the 'godmother' of ''[[Cantando Por Un Sue<U+00F1>o (song)|Cantando Por Un Sue<U+00F1>o]]'', a Mexican TV reality show. It was rumored she got paid 1 million dollars to perform. Thal<U+00ED>a recorded the title song of the show, and it was included in the album. It was released in Mexico on February 13, 2006 (U.S. June 6, Spain May 29) and features four new songs, including a duet with the group [[Aventura (band)|Aventura]], "[[No, no, no (Thal<U+00ED>a song)|No, No, No]]" which become a massive hit. "El Sexto Sentido" was nominated for one Latin Grammy as "Best Female Pop Vocal Album", it was also nominated in one Latin Billboard category <U+2013> "Pop Female Album" and in eight Premios Juventud categories.

In 2006, Thal<U+00ED>a became a U.S. citizen at a swearing-in ceremony in New York, where she resides with her husband. Under Mexican law she is allowed to retain her Mexican citizenship.

In March 2007, Thal<U+00ED>a also joined ABC Radio to start ''The Conexi<U+00F3>n Thal<U+00ED>a Radio Show'', where she talks about music, fashion, news and political issues.

Afterwards, she was named one of the 50 Most Beautiful People in ''[[People en Espa<U+00F1>ol]]'' 2008 for a record-breaking seventh time where they called her their "Queen". She was once again featured in the 2010 edition for an eighth time.

In May 2008, Thal<U+00ED>a's single "[[Ten Paciencia]]", was premiered on the internet.<ref>{{Cite news |title=On Sale Today!! Thal<U+00ED>a "Lunada"(EMI)|url=http://www.emitelevisa.com/portal/hgxpp001.aspx?11,8,263,O,E,0,PAG;CONC;23;21;D;1793342;1;PAG;MNU;E;72;220;MNU;,}}</ref> Although, the single received a lukewarm response and did not perform well in the U.S. charts and Top 20 hits in Mexico, it was #1 in several countries of Latin America. Furthermore, her tenth studio album ''[[Lunada]]'', was released on June 24, 2008 and debuted at number eight in Mexico and peaked at number ten on the Billboard Top Latin Albums (U.S). It was the last Thal<U+00ED>a's studio album released by [[EMI]].

Thal<U+00ED>a later appeared on ''El Show De Cristina'', aired in late July by Univision's Spanish network to promote the album. According to Univision network, her appearance on the show received huge ratings, reaching No. 1 in both the Chicago and Miami markets. The show was said to have been viewed by over 87 million people in the US alone.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Thal<U+00ED>a and the Cristina Show scored major TV ratings !|url=http://thalia3arabia.blogspot.com/2008/08/thalia-and-cristina-show-scored-major.html}}</ref>

"[[Ser<U+00E1> porque te amo]]", the second single, received no promotion and became another failed single. It is a Spanish language cover version of the Italian hit "Sar<U+00E0> perch<U+00E9> ti amo", originally performed by the group [[Ricchi e Poveri]].

On October 23, it was announced that Thal<U+00ED>a was suffering from [[Lyme disease]], which is transmitted by ticks. Fortunately, it was discovered quickly, and the singer, as well as her mother, Yolanda Miranda, were able to receive antibiotics in time.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Thal<U+00ED>a is suffering from Lyme disease|url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/pespanol/en/articles/0,22490,1853205,00.html}}</ref> On November 18, Thal<U+00ED>a announced the end of her collaboration with [[EMI Music]].

Despite Lunada being a commercial disappointment, it was named as the "Best Album of the Year" by [[<U+00A1>Hola!]] readers.<ref>{{Cite news |title='Lunada', de Thal<U+00ED>a, elegido mejor disco de 2008|url=http://www.hola.com/musica/2008/12/13/mejor-disco-2008/}}</ref> The latest work of the Mexican singer achieved 8,750 votes beating artists, such as [[Luis Miguel]], [[Britney Spears]], [[Mariah Carey]], [[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles|Beyonc<U+00E9>]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].<ref>{{Cite news |title= 'Lunada' named as Best Album of the Year by Hola readers|url=http://nuestrathalia.com/2008/12/15/lunada-named-as-best-album-of-the-year-by-hola-readers/}}</ref>

===2009<U+2013>2011: Success of ''Primera Fila'' and ''Growing Stronger''===
[[File:ThaliaSodi cropped.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Thalia]]

On July 30, 2009, Thal<U+00ED>a recorded her [[Acoustic music|acoustic]] album, ''[[Primera fila (Thal<U+00ED>a album)|Primera fila]]'', her first album after she signed with [[Sony Music Entertainment]].<ref>http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/92275.html</ref><ref>http://www.peopleenespanol.com/article/thalia-firma-con-sony-bmg-grabara-disco-acustico-en-vivo</ref> In October, Thal<U+00ED>a performed at the [[White House]], along with other Latin singers, in an event organized by President [[Barack Obama]] that celebrated [[Hispanic]] heritage. Thal<U+00ED>a's performance was iconic and historic, as she was the first celebrity to publicly invite a United States President to dance.<ref>http://www.terra.com.mx/musica/articulo/877798/Obama+baila+con+Thalia+en+Fiesta+Latina+de+la+Casa+Blanca.htm</ref>

In October of the same year, she released the first single from ''Primera fila'', a song named [[Equivocada]]. In December Thal<U+00ED>a released her album, which contained duets with [[Joan Sebastian]] and [[Pedro Cap<U+00F3>]] and various other songs, that became huge radio hits in the following months. The production received critical accept and very positive reviews, while Jason Birchmeier stated that "Primera Fila" was one of the best albums Thal<U+00ED>a has released in her whole career, and definitely the one with the most surprises.<ref>http://www.allmusic.com/album/thalia-en-primera-fila-sony-music-mw0001326602</ref> As for Thal<U+00ED>a, she considered [[Primera Fila (Thal<U+00ED>a album)|Primera Fila]] as "the most personal album" in her career.<ref>http://www.google.com/hostednews/epa/article/ALeqM5gRe6j2uCy1-sAbFPbkG6ZDsbqWyA</ref>

Regarding to the album's commercial performance, ''Primera fila'' received diamond and triple platinum sales certifications in Mexico, where it was announced by the end of 2011 that the album had sold over 500,000 copies according to [[Asociaci<U+00F3>n Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas|AMPROFON]].<ref>http://www.informador.com.mx/entretenimiento/2010/221942/6/thalia-celebra-el-primer-aniversario-de-su-primera-fila.htm</ref> ''Primera fila'' was the best selling album in Mexico in 2010, where it topped the charts for 55 non-consecutive weeks, the most weeks ever in Mexico's recorded music chart history.<ref>http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/primerafilaeldiscomasvendidoelanodethalia-619938.html</ref> In [[Greece]] and Spain, the album reached the positions No. 6 and No. 32, respectively, while it reached No. 4 in ''[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard's]]'' top Latin Albums<ref name="billboard.com">http://www.billboard.com/charts/2009-12-19/latin-albums</ref><ref name="ReferenceA">http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-10-23/latin-pop-albums</ref> and No. 2 in Billboard's Latin Pop Albums<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref>http://www.billboard.com/charts/2009-12-19/latin-pop-albums</ref> charts.  Initially, ''Primera Fila'' had reached No. 1 on both aforementioned charts, but sales of the standard edition and the Walmart edition were later divided, leading to a retraction and update to Billboard's official peak positions for ''Primera Fila''.  After these changes, ''Primera fila'' went from a peak position of #167 to a peak position of #198 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart.<ref name="billboard.com"/> Until the month of October 2012, ''Primera fila'' had sold over 1,5 million copies worldwide.<ref>http://mx.noticias.yahoo.com/disco-thalia-hab%C3%ADtame-%C3%ADntimo-cargado-sentimientos-212230030.html</ref><ref>http://www.impremedia.com/article/20121016/IMPORT01/310169970</ref>

In September 2010, Thal<U+00ED>a released a special anniversary edition of the album under the title ''Primera fila... Un a<U+00F1>o despu<U+00E9>s'', which included 8 songs from the original album, as well as 2 never-released before songs, 2 remixes and a DVD with a documentary of the recording process of the album. In October 2010, [[Michael Bubl<U+00E9>]] invited her to record a song with him in his holiday album ''[[Christmas (Michael Bubl<U+00E9> album)|Christmas]]''. Together they recorded the bilingual song <U+00AB>Mis Deseos/Feliz Navidad<U+00BB> and their collaboration received very positive reviews.<ref>http://www.allmusic.com/album/christmas-mw0001449190</ref>

===2012<U+2013>present: ''Habitame Siempre'' and ''VIVA! Tour''===

Thal<U+00ED>a had a collaboration with American music veteran [[Tony Bennett]] for his "Viva:Duets" album, which was released on October 22, 2012. Together they performed live the classic song "The way you look tonight" in Today's show and the [[Katie Couric|Katie Couric's]] show.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nbclatino.com/2012/10/23/thalia-makes-today-show-appearance-with-stellar-tony-bennett-duet/| work=[[NBC]] Latino|publisher=| title=Thalia makes Today Show appearance with stellar Tony Bennett duet|author=Nina Terrero| date=October 23, 2012}}</ref>

During the past months, she had announced that she was recording her eleventh studio album, ''[[Hab<U+00ED>tame siempre]]''. On September 21, 2012, Thal<U+00ED>a gave a private concert in New York City at [[Hammerstein Ballroom]] as a preview of the upcoming album. The album's lead single, "[[Man<U+00ED>as]]", was released on October 8, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.filmeweb.net/magazine.asp?id=8895|title=Thal<U+00ED>a shows her new "Manias"|work=Filmeweb.net|date=October 13, 2012|accessdate=October 15, 2012|language=Spanish}}</ref>

[[Hab<U+00ED>tame siempre]] was released in November 19, 2012 in the United States and Latin America under the label of [[Sony Music Latin]], while in Europe it is set to be released in 2013 by [[Sony BMG|BMG Music]]. The album contains collaborations with [[Robbie Williams]], [[Michael Bubl<U+00E9>]], [[Prince Royce]] and [[Gilberto Santa Rosa]], among others and immensely after its release, it received mostly positive reviews.

''"Habitame Siempre"'' was certified [[platinum certification|triple platinum]] plus [[gold certification|gold]] in Mexico for sales of more than 210,000 copies, [[gold certification|gold]] in the United States for shipments exceeding 50,000 copies and [[platinum certification|platinum]] in Venezuela for over 10,000 copies shipped.<ref>http://www.elentrerios.com/index.php/entretenimiento/music/39087-thalia-numero-uno-en-ventas-en-estados-unidos-</ref> In the meantime the second single of the album, "[[Te Perdiste Mi Amor]]", was certified [[platinum certification|platinum]] in Mexico for digital sales of over 60,000 copies.

In March 24, 2013 Thal<U+00ED>a launched her [[The VIVA! Tour|VIVA! Tour]] in support of [[Hab<U+00ED>tame Siempre]]. [[The VIVA! Tour]] marks Thal<U+00ED>a's first tour in a decade and consists of a series of intimate concerts in the United States and  Mexico. Thal<U+00ED>a stated in an interview that she also plans to expand the tour to Latin America, Europe and Asia if it meets positive commercial reception.

In October 2013, Thal<U+00ED>a released in the United States and Latin America her fourth book ''Chupie (The Binky That Returned Home)'' and in November 12, Thal<U+00ED>a released in Mexico her second live album ''VIVA! Tour''. This album was recorded in April 27, 2013 during her concert in Mexico City. In United States and Latin America, the album was released in December 1, 2013. It was certified [[gold certification|gold]] in [[Mexico]] on its second week on the market for sales exceeding 30,000 copies.

On July 22, 2014, the singer Italian <U+00AB>Global superstar<U+00BB> [[Laura Pausini]] confirmed that by September that same year she would release a special version of her [[20 - The Greatest Hits|Greatest Hits album]] to the hispanophone market, in an edition containing new duet with Thal<U+00ED>a in ''[[Se non te|Sino a ti]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/televisione/2014/notizia/laura-pausini-sara-coach-a-la-voz-mexico-_2058857.shtml|publisher=TGcom24|title=Laura Pausini sar<U+00E0> coach a La voz... M<U+00E9>xico}}</ref>

==Acting career==

[[File:Thalia Mar<U+00ED>a.jpg|thumb|right|150px|<center>[[Mar<U+00ED>a la del barrio]], Thal<U+00ED>a's 1995 record-setting [[telenovela]] that was broadcast in more than 180 countries''.</center>]]
Thalia was cast in a supporting role in the 1986 [[telenovela]] "Pobre se<U+00F1>orita Limantour", with which she began her collaboration with [[Televisa]], the largest mass media company in the Spanish-speaking world. In 1987, she went on to star in her first major role for Televisa in the 1987 teenage drama series ''[[Quincea<U+00F1>era (telenovela)|Quincea<U+00F1>era]]'', along with Mexican actress [[Adela Noriega]]. "Quincea<U+00F1>era" won the "TV y Novelas" award for Best Telenovela of the Year 1988. In 1989, she got her first lead role in "Luz y Sombra", which was less successful.

However, Thal<U+00ED>a's explosion in popularity came in 1992, when she starred in "[[Maria Mercedes (telenovela)|Mar<U+00ED>a Mercedes]]" for which she won a "TV Y Novelas" award as Best Young Actress in 1993. This series was the first of three telenovelas, named by the Mexican press as "Las Tres Marias" ("The Three Mar<U+00ED>as"), because the name of the heroine in all of these telenovelas was ''Mar<U+00ED>a''. The second telenovela of the trilogy was "[[Marimar (telenovela)|Marimar]]" in 1994, and the third and final was "[[Maria la del Barrio]]" in 1995. In 1999, Thal<U+00ED>a starred in her latest telenovela, "[[Rosalinda (telenovela)|Rosalinda]]". All four telenovelas were basically based on the same rags to riches character.<ref name="tevnovelas.blogspot.gr">http://tevnovelas.blogspot.gr/2011/07/thalia-legendary-telenovela-actresses.html</ref>
With these [[telenovelas]], Thal<U+00ED>a became famous worldwide and was consolidated as a television phenomenon, because of the extremely high ratings her TV series achieved in more than 180 countries (especially [[Philippines]]).<ref name="tevnovelas.blogspot.gr"/><ref>http://www.celebritynetworth.com/richest-celebrities/singers/thalia-mottola-net-worth/</ref>

Although Thal<U+00ED>a's presence in television is legendary, her presence in [[Filmmaking|cinema]] is less important. She appeared for the first time in a movie when she was still a child in the 1979 film "La Guerra De los Pasteles" ("The War of the Cakes"). Furthermore, in 1999, she starred in ''"Mambo Caf<U+00E9>"'', a modest [[independent film|indie]] film production that had a poor reception from critics, as it was a low budget film.

===Cultural impact of telenovelas===

Thal<U+00ED>a has been labeled by various mass media companies as the "queen of soap operas",<ref name="delafont">http://delafont.com/music_acts/thalia.htm</ref> because her presence in television during the decade of the 90s was phenomenal. She starred in Mexico's highest-rated [[telenovelas]] ever that were exported in over 180 countries and viewed by more than 2 billion people. It is stated by media experts that at some point at the midst of the telenovela craze, Thal<U+00ED>a's name even became synonymous with her native country, [[Mexico]].

According to the newspaper "Ivoir'Soir": "At 7.30 sharp in the evening, when Marimar comes on, everything stops in Cote d'Ivoire". It is also mentioned that "Marimar" could attract more local fans than the 1998 World Cup, and that the program arrived in Africa after being a phenomenal rating hit in Indonesia and the Philippines, where in 1997 she was received in [[Manila]] like a foreign [[head of state]].<ref>http://www.questia.com/library/1G1-54738757/soaps-with-a-latin-scent</ref>

Thal<U+00ED>a stated in her autobiography regarding to the impact of her [[telenovelas]]: "Soap operas made a lot of history; just look at the report by UNESCO, where it was noted that "in the [[Ivory Coast]] in Africa and in Paris (France), people stopped the daily course of their lives just to watch a soap opera. I never expected that kind of success [...] Whenever I arrived anywhere, I was treated like royalty; even the press in some of these countries referred to me as the Aztec Queen, the Mexican Queen, or the ambassador of Mexico, and like a proud peacock, I always brought my country's flag with me wherever I went to represent my motherland. I was in the clouds at the pinnacle of my career [...] During my visit at the Philippines, the organizers informed me that the last time so many people gathered in the streets for a person was when [[Pope John Paul II|Pope John Paul the Second]] came to visit on January fourteenth, 1995 [...] In the Philippines, the country that probably felt the greatest impact from Marimar, the show was more widely promoted than the 1998 World Cup and more highly rated than the Super Bowl or the Grammys. In fact while I was visiting the country, the people and the media were so enthralled to see [[Marimar (telenovela)|Marimar]] in the flesh that a historic peace treaty between the government and the querillas and the centennial celebrations of the [[Philippine Revolution]]s that were happening at the same time were pushed aside in the midst of Marimar fever. As a result, the archipelago was temporarily dubbed "Rep<U+00FA>blica de MariMar."

The phenomenon of Thal<U+00ED>a's telenovelas also became visible in countries like [[Indonesia]], [[Turkey]], [[Greece]], [[Hungary]], [[Poland]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Romania]], [[Russia]], [[Brazil]], [[Lebanon]], [[France]], [[Egypt]], [[Portugal]] and the majority of Spanish-speaking countries around the world.<ref>http://www.pep.ph/spotlight/looking-back/13166/The-Marimar-Craze</ref>

==Business activities==

[[File:ThaliaVisionExpo2007.jpg|thumb|left|<center>Thal<U+00ED>a in a Visi<U+00F3>n Expo event in 2007, presenting her eyewear collections''.</center>]]

[[File:Thal<U+00ED>a caricatura 2008-04.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Thalia [[cartoon]]]]

In 2002, Thal<U+00ED>a signed a deal with [[Kmart Corporation|Kmart]] in order to release her own clothing collection for women, as well as accessories and home products. In the middle of 2003, the "Thal<U+00ED>a Sodi" collection was officially available in the US market in over 2,000 stores. Thal<U+00ED>a commented: <U+00AB>My collection is a dream that came through. I'm so happy to have created a clothe line inspired by my culture, trying to show the colors and the passion of our culture, that captures also a big part of my personal style<U+00BB>. Thal<U+00ED>a became the first Mexican woman to launch a clothing brand in the US.<ref>http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/43573.thalia-esta-a-la-venta.html</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/stories/2003/08/04/daily28.html | title=Kmart launches Thalia Sodi Collection in Miami}}</ref><ref>http://famosos.about.com/od/tuscantantesfavoritos/p/Pefil-De-Thal-Ia.htm</ref>

Simultaneously, Thal<U+00ED>a debuted her eyewear collection under the brand name "Thal<U+00ED>a Eyewear Collection" in association with Kenmark Optical.<ref>http://musica.univision.com/noticias/article/2002-04-21/thalia-mira-al-futuro-con</ref> In 2005, the line also became available in Mexico's market as Thal<U+00ED>a signed a deal with "Devlyn" company.<ref>http://www.elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id=53859</ref> Up to 2007 Thal<U+00ED>a had generated 100 million $US from the sales of <U+00AB>Thal<U+00ED>a Eyewear<U+00BB>, with more than 1 million products sold.<ref>http://www2.esmas.com/ritmoson-latino/artistas/054422/thalia?country_code=US</ref> Precisely in 2007 Thal<U+00ED>a presented a new eyewear collection in New York, and the brand was exported to over eighty countries around the world.<ref>http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/156121/Thalia+presento+su+nueva+linea+de+lentes.htm</ref>

[[File:Thalia girl.gif|thumb|right|300px|Thalia logo]]

In April 2004, Thal<U+00ED>a entered the editorial market by releasing her own magazine ''Thal<U+00ED>a'' in US, produced by American Media and oriented to the female Latin youth. The magazine included consultation and reports about themes like health, fashion and beauty secrets.<ref>http://www.writenews.com/2004/043004_ami_thalia.htm</ref> Some months later, in September, Thal<U+00ED>a became the face of jewels' company Jacob & Co.<ref>http://web.archive.org/web/20081001214807/http://www.jacobandco.com/thalia04a.pdf</ref>

In 2004, Thal<U+00ED>a signed a contract with [[The Hershey Company|Hershey's]] with which she released her chocolate and candy brand.<ref>http://stilo.es/contenido/noticias/2004/0404/1404/noticias_stilo-140404/noticias_stilo-140404-9.htm</ref><ref>http://www.hersheys.com.mx/03Promociones/thalia/productos.html</ref> In 2005 Thal<U+00ED>a designed a summer clothe line,<ref>http://www.terra.com/mujer/articulo/html/hof20159.htm</ref> and in the following year, she was converted into the face of "Carol<U+2019>s Daughter" company, specialized in beauty products,<ref>http://www.ahorroslarevista.com/2011/08/exitosa-thalia/</ref> while in 2007 she launched her perfume, produced by "Fuller Cosmetics" company.<ref>http://elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id=26733</ref><ref>http://www.elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id=32003</ref> In 2007, she joined ABC Radio and started her own radio show known as "The Conexi<U+00F3>n Thal<U+00ED>a Radio Show", in which she discusses music, fashion, news and political issues, and invites various people to talk with her on different issues.<ref>http://abcradionetworks.com/Article.asp?id=416838</ref> The program, that is weekly and lasts two hours premiered on March 17, 2007 and still goes on, while it has expanded to over 70 radio stations through the US.

In September 2007, she released "Thal<U+00ED>a: <U+00A1>Belleza!-Lessons in Lipgloss and Happiness"<ref>http://www.chroniclebooks.com/index/main,book-info/store,books/products_id,6716/</ref> while in June 2009, she released her second book entitled "Thalia: <U+00A1>Radiante!-Your Guide to a Fit and a Fabulous Pregnancy". In May 2010, Thal<U+00ED>a revealed new accessories and jewels available via her website, apart from a new clothing line in association with multinational company [[C&A]].<ref>http://impreso.elnuevodiario.com.ni/2010/05/11/variedades/124062</ref> In February 2011, she became the new face of [[Head & Shoulders]] and in November, she released her third book, which is her autobiography and named "Growing Stronger".<ref>http://www.merca20.com/thalia-nueva-imagen-de-head-shoulders/</ref> Thal<U+00ED>a has also been the public face of various advertisements, like [[Dr Pepper]] in 2001 or [[Victoria's Secret]] in 2005. According to ''Mira!'' magazine, in 2008 it was estimated that Thal<U+00ED>a was one of the most wealthy Mexican businesswomen with a net worth of over 100 million $US.<ref>http://sonfamosos.com/2008/02/28/thalia-es-la-mas-rica-de-mexico-con-100-millones-de-dolares/</ref> In April 2012, she inaugurated her own yoga center in New York.<ref>http://entretenimiento.terra.com.mx/famosos/thalia-abre-centro-de-yoga-en-nueva-york,1456675b946c6310VgnVCM5000009ccceb0aRCRD.html</ref>

==Personal life==
Thal<U+00ED>a was in a relationship with actor [[Fernando Colunga]] from 1995 to 1996 at that time they work in [[Mar<U+00ED>a la del Barrio]] Thalia  married music executive [[Tommy Mottola]] in New York City at [[St. Patrick's Cathedral, New York|St. Patrick's Cathedral]] on December 2, 2000. Since then, she has been living in [[Connecticut]] with her husband and their two children, a daughter named Sabrina Sakae and a son named Matthew Alejandro.<ref>{{Cite news |title=People: Thal<U+00ED>a is pregnant!|url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/pespanol/en/articles/0,22490,1722075_1632035,00.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/1058211/Thalia+esta+embarazada+de+su+segundo+hijo.htm |title=Thal<U+00ED>a est<U+00E1> embarazada de su segundo hijo <U+2013> Famosos <U+2013> Entretenimiento |publisher=Terra |date= |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref>

Thal<U+00ED>a has stated in her autobiography and in various of her interviews, that she has a deep connection with religion, and believes profoundly in God. She also began studying [[Kabbalah]] in 2002, while she used many of its symbols in the artwork of her album [[El Sexto Sentido]].<ref>http://www.thalia.com/elsextosentido/</ref>

In September 2002, Thal<U+00ED>a's sisters, Laura Zapata and Ernestina Sodi, were kidnapped in Mexico City. Zapata was released 18 days after her kidnapping, and her sister Ernestina was released on the 36th day.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/29/world/world-briefing-the-americas-mexico-kidnapped-writer-freed.html | work=The New York Times  | title=Kidnapped writer freed | date=October 29, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/12/world/world-briefing-americas-mexico-kidnapped-actress-freed.html | work=[[The New York Times]]| title=Kidnapped actrees freed | date=October 12, 2002}}</ref> Thal<U+00ED>a has had a series of familial conflicts, especially with her sister [[Laura Zapata]]. However, she has opted to keep her point of view regarding to her familial issues in privacy, despite the attacks she has received from her elder sister.<ref>http://www.elnuevodia.com/thaliausalamusicaparasanar-1364529.html</ref> In a press interview, Thal<U+00ED>a stated that her familial problems with her sister are "just a dark cloud in a shiny sky".<ref>http://entretenimiento.univision.com/chismes/noticias/article/2012-10-18/los-problemas-familiares-no-afectan-a-thalia</ref>

In 2008, Thal<U+00ED>a was affected by [[Lyme disease]], a disease commonly transmitted by [[ticks]]. Thal<U+00ED>a's illness prevented her from promoting her album [[Lunada]], while it functioned as a motivation for her to have a totally different perspective towards life.<ref name="lymedisease.org">http://lymedisease.org/news/touchedbylyme/thalia.html</ref>
In reference to her illness, Thalia stated in her autobiography : <U+201C>I would sweat profusely, soaking my pajamas, the sheets and even the mattress; everything hurt, even my hair, which, by the way, started to fall out. At times it felt as if my head were going to burst, as if there were lead inside of it; my eyes ached in their sockets<U+2026>.the hypersensitivity of my skin was so severe that sometimes I couldn<U+2019>t even handle the bed sheets.<U+201D><ref name="lymedisease.org"/>

==Humanitarian work==

Thal<U+00ED>a has participated in various humanitarian campaigns. Since 2004, she has been an official celebrity ambassador and volunteer of [[March of Dimes]], in order to support national fundraising and awareness campaigns. [[March of Dimes]] is a United States nonprofit organization that works to improve the health of mothers and babies.<ref>http://www.nacersano.org/prematuro/9322_10434.asp</ref> Through various public service campaigns and through her own media channels, Thalia has been a strong voice for March of Dimes Prematurity Campaign. She also is featured in March of Dimes Education and Health Promotion materials in English and Spanish, while she has helped to raise awareness and critical funds for the March of Dimes year-round. Furthermore, she supports March for Babies and works to find ongoing opportunities for March of Dimes strategic alliances and media promotions.<ref>http://www.marchofdimes.com/spotlights/spotlight_thalia.html</ref>
<ref>http://www.esmas.com/espectaculos/farandula/486899.html</ref>

In 2006, Thal<U+00ED>a along with her husband attended the event ''A Funny Thing Happened On The Way To Cure Parkinson's'' with the aim to economically support the foundation ''The Michael J. Fox Foundation for Parkinson's Research'' of [[Michael J. Fox]].<ref>http://www.labotana.com/index.php/celebridades/14627-0737-christian-chavez-no-quiere-ser-vocero-oficial-de-la-comunidad-gay</ref><ref>http://www.hola.com/noticias-de-actualidad/06-11-2008/60900/</ref>

In May 2009, Thal<U+00ED>a and Tommy Mottola were recognized from St. Jude Children<U+2019>s Research Hospital in Miami for their support in children in need.<ref>http://www.elporvenir.com.mx/notas.asp?nota_id=304644</ref> In 2010, she reunited with other recording artists, performers and actors like [[Sharon Stone]], [[Michael Douglas]], [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Marc Anthony]] between others, in order to raise funds for the "Foundation of the New York's police department", which works for better urban security.<ref>http://www.quien.com/espectaculos/2010/03/18/thalia-apoya-a-la-policia-de-ny</ref> In 2011, she attended a beneficial event in New York, organized by the ''Robin Hood Foundation'' with the aim to raise money for homeless youth.<ref>http://www.antena3.com/celebrities/famosos-fiesta/celebrities-acuden-gala-fundacion-robin-hood_2011051002237.html</ref><ref>http://www.quien.com/fotogalerias/2011/05/10/thalia-en-la-gala-de-la-fundacion-robin-hood</ref> In the same year, she closed the Mexican [[Telet<U+00F3>n (Mexico)|Teleton]] by offering a live concert.<ref>http://www2.esmas.com/entretenimiento/musica/noticias/372910/thalia-cerrara-teleton-2011</ref><ref>http://entretenimiento.starmedia.com/musica/concierto-thalia-en-cierre-teleton-2011.html</ref><ref>http://noticiasespectaculos.info/teleton-2011-supero-la-meta-recaudando-471-472925-pesos/</ref>

Thal<U+00ED>a is also a member of "[[ALAS Foundation]]", which is a non-profit organization that strives to launch a new social movement that will generate a collective commitment to comprehensive Early Childhood Development programs for the children in Latin America.<ref>http://www.lasnoticiasmexico.com/112925.html</ref>

In November 2012, Thal<U+00ED>a took humanitarian aid and comfort to compatriots of her in New York that were affected by [[Hurricane Sandy]]. She stated : <U+201C>When I started seeing the destruction of Sandy I thought it was incredible, but, when I saw my Mexican brothers and sisters I felt the need to try and do something for them<U+201D> in front of a group of families gathered at the Staten Island Immigrant Information Center in one of the most devastated by the storm areas. She went on to say that in times like this an artist should use the reach of the media to collect aid for the victims, and at the same time she called on the public to deposit money in the account opened by the Mexican Consulate for that purpose.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2012/11/09/thalia-distributes-aid-to-mexican-immigrants-affected-by-sandy/#ixzz2BlZQYZKU | work=Fox News | title=Thalia distributes aid to Mexican immigrants affected by Sandy | date=November 9, 2012}}</ref>

In April 2013, Thal<U+00ED>a was awarded with the "Your Voice Inspires Many" award by the ''Lyme Research Alliance''.<ref>http://thaliaforever.com/2013/04/07/foto-thalia-attends-time-for-lyme-gala-06-04-2013/</ref>

==Influences==

According to Thalia herself, her major personal influence was her mother, who was a motivating manager for Thalia from the very beginning of her career until 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entretenimiento.univision.com/fotos/populares/slideshow/2011-05-27/miranda-con-thalia-y-sus-hijas-en-foto |title=Los momentos de Miranda con Thal<U+00ED>a y sus hijas |publisher=Univision Entretenimiento |date= |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref> As for her artistic influences, Thalia's work is mostly influenced by [[Gloria Estefan]], [[Celine Dion]], [[Sade (band)|Sade]], [[Billie Holiday]], [[Frank Sinatra]], [[The Doors]], [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Kylie Minogue]],<ref name="abullseyeview"/> while she has stated that she always admired [[Marilyn Monroe]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]. Thalia's first idol, according to her, was athlete [[Nadia Comaneci]]. She has even stated that her record-breaking performance was a huge motivation for her to follow a career in entertainment.

==Legacy==
[[File:Thalia and Barack Obama cropped.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Thal<U+00ED>a invites United States President [[Barack Obama]] to dance with her while performing her signature hit "Amor a la mexicana" at the "In Performance at the White House: Fiesta Latina".]]

Thalia has been also an influential artist for almost every Latin pop singer, while [[Julio Iglesias]], [[Tony Bennett]], [[Juan Luis Guerra]], [[Gloria Estefan]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Carlos Vives]], [[Tiziano Ferro]], [[Michael Bubl<U+00E9>]], [[Shakira]], [[Lindsay Lohan]], [[Anahi]], [[Espinoza Paz]], [[Gloria Trevi]], [[Inna]], [[Erik Rubin]], [[Pedro Cap<U+00F3>]] and many other artists have expressed their admiration towards her talent and charisma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com/entretenimiento/noticias/Lindsay_lohan_quiere_ser_como_thalia/oci64881 |title=Lindsay Lohan quiere ser como... Thal<U+00ED>a! |publisher=Terra |date= |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://laprimeraplana.com.mx/2011/09/21/espinoza-paz-quiere-grabar-dueto-con-thalia/ |title=Espinoza Paz quiere grabar dueto con Thal<U+00ED>a |publisher=La Primera Plana |date=September 22, 2011 |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=El Siglo de Torre<U+00F3>n|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/89772.tiziano-ferro-quiere-componer-para-thalia.html |title=Tiziano Ferro quiere componer para Thal<U+00ED>a / Espect<U+00E1>culos |publisher=Elsiglodetorreon.com.mx |date=May 22, 2004 |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imagendelgolfo.com.mx/resumen.php?id=301599 |title=Inna viene la reina del Dance Music |publisher=Agencia Imagen del Golfo |date=March 14, 2012 |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com.mx/books?id=7RMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA7-IA4&dq=thal%C3%ADa+arrasando+billboard&hl=es&sa=X&ei=Bo17T725Fuih2QXx0ISNAw&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=thal%C3%ADa%20arrasando%20billboard&f=false |title=Billboard <U+2013> Google Libros |publisher=Books.google.com.mx |date= |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref>

According to the American magazine "[[Ocean Drive]]", Thalia is "the biggest star that has exported Mexico in recent decades."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archivo.laprensa.com.ni/archivo/2001/noviembre/09/aquientrenos/diversion/diversion-20011109-04.html|title=Far<U+00E1>ndula: Thal<U+00ED>a arrasando con todo|work=[[La Prensa (Managua)]]|author=[[Ocean Drive]]|year=2001|accessdate=November 25, 2013}}</ref> [[Univision Communications]] included her in their list of "25 most influential Mexican musicians",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oyemexico.com/nota/25-mexicanos-mas-influyentes-en-la-musica/ |title=25 mexicanos mas influyentes en la m<U+00FA>sica |publisher=Oyemexico.com |date= |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref> while she holds a record for appearing the most times in People en Espa<U+00F1>ol's annual list of the most beautiful Latin celebrities. The same magazine chose her in 2011 as one of the most powerful Latin women. The British tabloid "[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]" declared Thalia as the 25th female singer who will never be forgotten.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letras.com.br/noticia/as-50-cantoras-que-nunca-serao-esquecidas_334 |title=Revista Cifras <U+2013> Not<U+00ED>cias sobre M<U+00FA>sica e Entretenimento em Tempo Real |publisher=Letras.com.br |date=July 26, 2012 |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref> In 1998, French company [[Louis Vuitton]] invited her to appear in Rebonds publication, being at the time the first Latin celebrity to appear in such an important book.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sandra Rodr<U+00ED>guez |url=http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/18798/Es+Thalia+la+unica+latina+en+Rebonds.htm |title=Es Thal<U+00ED>a la <U+00FA>nica latina en 'Rebonds' <U+2013> M<U+00FA>sica <U+2013> Gente E |publisher=Terra |date= |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref> In 1997, April 25 was declared by the government of Los Angeles, as Thalia's National Day, because of her growing popularity among the Latino community in the United States.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com.mx/books?id=STjcB_f7CVcC&lpg=PA835&dq=thalia%20m%C3%A9xico&hl=es&pg=PA835#v=onepage&q=thalia&f=false |title=Encyclopedia of Latino Popular Culture <U+2013> Cordelia Candelaria, Peter J. Garc<U+00ED>a, Arturo J. Aldama |publisher=Books.google.com.mx |date= |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref>

{{Quote box|align=right|width=30%|quote="Thal<U+00ED>a has built one of the most successful global Latino races in memory."|source=<U+2014>[[Leila Cobo]] from [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]].<ref name="bbissue">{{cite journal|last=Leila|first=Cobo|date=October 22, 2005|title=<nowiki>Thal<U+00ED>a (cont.) | Beyond Glitz, Thal<U+00ED>a Blazes Her Own Trail | Global Success (cont.) | At a Glance: Thalia's Soap Operas | Thalia's Chart Action</nowiki>|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|location=New York|volume=117|issue=43|issn=0006-2510|url=http://books.google.es/books?id=ERUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40&dq=Thal%C3%ADa+successful+global+Leila+Cobo&hl=es&sa=X&ei=Z8uTUs_MJ8u-kQfxyoC4Cg&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Thal%C3%ADa%20successful%20global%20Leila%20Cobo&f=false|ref=harv}}</ref> 
}}

Thalia's explosion in fame coincided with the worldwide broadcast of the soap operas she starred. During the decade of the 90s, she was highly promoted by television, achieving in this way to establish herself as an ultimate television phenomenon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetthalia.com/NewsArchivesNoticiasArchivos/tag/mexican-magic/ |title=Mexican Magic |publisher=PlanetThalia.com |date=August 27, 1996 |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref> Thalia's soap operas were viewed in more than 180 countries by almost 2 billion viewers,<ref name="delafont"/> giving her the opportunity to mark history in television and become one of the most successful television icons ever.<ref>[http://www.informador.com.mx/entretenimiento/2008/23025/6/debuta-disco-de-thalia-en-lugar-10-entre-latinos-mas-vendidos-en-eu.htm]{{dead link|date=October 2012}}</ref> After her achieving growing popularity, she took advantage of her fame in order to promote her music and try to open new markets with Spanish hits that entered the music charts of many countries. When in 1999, she starred in her last soap opera, [[Rosalinda (telenovela)|Rosalinda]], she abandoned the field of television in order to focus more in her music projects. In the 2000s, she gained commercial and critical recognition for her music projects, while she also entered the business market, by launching several products under her brand name,<ref>{{cite web|author=Josu<U+00E9> P. Camacho / El Mexicano |url=http://www.el-mexicano.com.mx/informacion/noticias/1/8/fama/2011/07/23/489329/sigue-cosechando-exitos.aspx |title=2011/07/23 Sigue cosechando <U+00E9>xitos -El Mexicano |publisher=El-mexicano.com.mx |date=July 23, 2011 |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref> and dominated the editorial business by writing and releasing three books, that became bestsellers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Thalia-Radiante-Ultimate-Fabulous-Pregnancy/dp/B0035G02W2/ref=pd_sxp_grid_pt_0_1 |title=Thalia Radiante: The Ultimate Guide to a Fit and Fabulous Pregnancy: Thalia |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=October 22, 2012}}</ref>

It has been announced that in 2013, she will receive her own star in the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] as a recognition to her versatile trajectory and her legacy in the world of music and entertainment.<ref name="abullseyeview"/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/26/thalia-hollywood-walk-of-fame_n_1628329.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Lee | last=Hernandez | title=Thal<U+00ED>a To Get Star On Hollywood Walk Of Fame | date=June 26, 2012}}</ref>

